Project Overview

One reason I picked Canva was how easily it lets you organize ideas without wrestling with software. Its ready-made layouts aimed at learners gave me a head start. What helped most was being able to move elements around freely, like arranging pieces on paper. Focusing on what mattered - clear flow of information - felt natural here. Design skills weren’t needed thanks to smart defaults guiding each choice.
Picture this: my infographic walks new students through digital know-how using three clear ideas - what digital literacy means, how to stay safe online. 
To back that up, I built profiles on GitHub, LinkedIn, Kaggle. Each one plays a different role. Think of GitHub as where my coding lives - it tracks changes, displays live work. 
Then there's LinkedIn, which holds my experience, connects me with internship paths. As for Kaggle? That’s the spot where I train skills in data science, using hands-on challenges. These tools together shape how I grow technically. Starting fresh here made things click.
My GitHub profile README started as a way to say who I am to people involved in open source. Meanwhile, on LinkedIn, updates show where I stand right now with studies at VIT Bhopal University. Through the coming four years, how I apply both platforms will shape up slowly. Every key school project finds its home on GitHub, so that when degree time arrives, proof of work already exists. Following professionals there helps me stay close to real-world trends, and also opens doors for summer roles through former students now working out there. One last thing - Kaggle becomes where I test myself through challenges, slowly building sharper thinking. Starting these profiles now means showing up not only as a learner, but as someone others see, remember, and trust online.
